Imputing missing values

Note that there are a number of days/intervals where there are missing values (coded as NA). The presence of missing days may introduce bias into some calculations or summaries of the data.

  1. Calculate and report the total number of missing values in the dataset (i.e. the total number of rows with NAs)
sum(is.na(data$steps))
## [1] 2304
  1. Devise a strategy for filling in all of the missing values in the dataset. The strategy does not need to be sophisticated. For example, you could use the mean/median for that day, or the mean for that 5-minute interval, etc.
stepsperinterval <- data %>%
                    na.omit() %>%
                        group_by(interval) %>%
                        summarize(stepsmean = mean(steps)) %>% 
                        as.data.frame()

imputedata <- numeric()
for (i in 1:nrow(data)) {
    x <- data[i, ]
    if (is.na(x$steps)) {
        steps <- subset(stepsperinterval, interval == x$interval)$steps
    } else {
        steps <- x$steps
    }
    imputedata <- c(imputedata, steps)
}
  1. Create a new dataset that is equal to the original dataset but with the missing data filled in.
newdata <- data
newdata$steps <- imputedata

  1. Make a histogram of the total number of steps taken each day newby.day <- group_by(newdata, date) newsteps <- summarize(newby.day, stepsperday = sum(steps)) hist(newsteps$stepsperday, xlab = “Steps Per Day”, main = “Histogram of Steps Per Day”)

Are there differences in activity patterns between weekdays and weekends?

  1. Create a new factor variable in the dataset with two levels – “weekday” and “weekend” indicating whether a given date is a weekday or weekend day.
weekday <- data$weekday
type <- vector()
for (i in 1:nrow(data)) {
    if (weekday[i] == "Saturday") {
        type[i] <- "Weekend"
    } else if (weekday[i] == "Sunday") {
        type[i] <- "Weekend"
    } else {
        type[i] <- "Weekday"
    }
}
data$type <- type
data$type <- factor(data$type)

stepsperint.type <- aggregate(steps ~ interval + type, data = data, mean)
  1. Make a panel plot containing a time series plot (i.e. type = “l”) of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the average number of steps taken, averaged across all weekday days or weekend days (y-axis). See the README file in the GitHub repository to see an example of what this plot should look like using simulated data.
xyplot(steps ~ interval | type, stepsperint.type, type = "l", layout = c(1, 2), 
    xlab = "Interval", ylab = "Number of Steps")
